Title : Asia-Pacific Fistball Championships
Text : [[File:Australian attacker serves at the 2014 Asian Fistball Championships.jpg|thumb|Australian attacker serves at the 2014 Asian Fistball Championships]]

'''Asia-Pacific Fistball Championships''' are an international [[fistball]] competition run in conjunction with the  [[International Fistball Association]] (IFA), and the [[Asia-Pacific Fistball Association]] (APFC) with the first men's championships held in Pakistan in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Asia Cup in Lahore/Pakistan was a tremendous success|url=http://www.ifa-fistball.com/en/menu_main/marketshow-first-asia-cup-in-lahorepakistan-was-a-tremendous-success|access-date=2014-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429202438/http://www.ifa-fistball.com/en/menu_main/marketshow-first-asia-cup-in-lahorepakistan-was-a-tremendous-success|archive-date=2014-04-29|dead-url=yes}}</ref> While originally known as the Asian Fistball Championships, the tournament has been renamed to the Asia-Pacific Fistball Championships for subsequent iterations, to recognise the inclusion of Oceanic region fistball associations such as Australia and New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|title=Fistball Federation of Australia to host 2nd Asia-Pacific Fistball Championships in 2018|url=http://fistball.com.au/fistball-federation-of-australia-to-host-2nd-asia-pacific-fistball-championships-in-2018}}</ref>. The participating countries in the first Asia-Pacific Fistball Championships were Pakistan, India, Australia and Nepal.

